  • Sensitive Touch Panel This smart dimmer switch is equipped with a sensitive touch panel that allows you simply slide your finger on the panel to adjust the brightness of light bulbs. Delicate radian, the skin-like matte surface and its exceptionally quiet rocker design are a great combination of beauty and technology. Vanishing brightness indicator makes the product look more simple and elegant. Supports incandescent bulbs up to 450W or dimmable LED bulbs up to 150W. UL and FCC certificated.
  • Control from Anywhere Replaces traditional 3-way switches commonly found in living rooms, stairways and hallways with the ELEGRP Smart WiFi dimmer switch. You can set the ambiance of the room with the simple push of a button. Tailor room lighting levels for any activity. And of course this ELEGRP wifi smart dimmer switch allows you remotely control the lights via APP on the smartphone anytime and anywhere.
  • Hands Free Voice Control Enjoy the hands-free convenience of controlling the lights in your home with your voice via Amazon Alexa or Google Assistant; You can simply say "Hi Alexa, set the bedroom light brightness to 60%" without getting up to dim or brighten the light when you are immersed in games, books, work or busy doing something.
  • Smart Scheduling and Scenes Use schedules or countdown timer to set your lights to automatically turn on and off at the time you want. Sync on and off times to sunrise and sunset, porch lights will greet you when you come home late. With the ELEGRP smart light switch, you can create your personalized smart scenes.
  • Easy to Install Ultra slim profile leaves more room in the electrical box for easy wiring. Step-by-step installation instructions will help you finish the wiring process quickly and easily. Works in a single-pole or 3 way setup. Neutral Wire is Required. Only supports 2.4G network (NOT 5G). No Hub Required. Input power: 120V AC 60Hz. UL and FCC certificated.

        Probably the best of the generic budget dimmers

        There were no reviews when I bought this, but the Lutron Caseta Diva just came out and finally looks better than the Levitons with their cheap looking plastic and green lights (Regular Casetas also look high quality, but theyre uglier than Levitons). Before I spent a... See more
        There were no reviews when I bought this, but the Lutron Caseta Diva just came out and finally looks better than the Levitons with their cheap looking plastic and green lights (Regular Casetas also look high quality, but theyre uglier than Levitons). Before I spent a fortune on the new Casetas, I thought Id give these a try.
        First, they look great. By any metric they are nicer than Levitons. I got the touchpad type ones and in was worried that function wouldnt work that well, but if you know where the sensitive area is, they work great.
        The app is decent. It lets you configure minimum dimming to avoid flicker on some lights that dont like being dimmed too low. You can configure ramping time. There are scenes, timers, and schedules (I havent tried these). All in all, I cant see a reason to buy any other smart dimmer over these unless you dont like the aesthetic. The covers that come with it are very slim (like Levitons), so if you have wider openings in your wall you might need to get midway covers (I use Eatons).
        I had just convinced myself that the casetas are worth it because they arent WIFI but I might end up using half these and half casetas in the house. If these were Zwave or Zigbee Id replace the whole house with them.

        A couple weeks later: still working good. My lights can dim all the way to 1% and these dimmers handle it pretty well. At very very low dinning I can see the light isnt completely steady but its not a real flicker, and my wife cant notice it at all. And by the way, you can use any Tuya app with these. I have them in Tuya Smart Life and integrated into Home Assistant. Next step will be seeing if they can work with local Tuya or even flashing them to use with esphome.

      • Amazon Customer
        4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
        Very nice looking switches. Great connectivity. Questionable QC.
        Reviewed in the United States on November 17, 2024
        Size: 3 WayColor: WhiteNumber of Items: 1
        I have a number of these switches wired in various configurations in my house. Overall, these are very nice. I particularly like that the 3 way switches dont have an on/off but simply that you can press either up or down for a toggle. Makes for a really intuitive setup... See more
        I have a number of these switches wired in various configurations in my house. Overall, these are very nice. I particularly like that the 3 way switches dont have an on/off but simply that you can press either up or down for a toggle. Makes for a really intuitive setup to press on regardless of where you are. That being said, Ive had some QC issues with my switches. A few have randomly failed within days/weeks of installation. Not a big deal, really. Just order a new one from Amazon and return the bad. Overall, I do like the switches quite a bit.

        Also worth noting, a number of these reviews are very misleading and Ill try to address the misconceptions due to others nativity.

        First - these switches will buzz when dimmed, but that is not the fault of the switch but the lights connected. Some of my LEDs will buzz the switch, others do not. Not the switches fault.

        Second - these are capable of dimming down to 1%. Again, your results will vary based on the bulb. Same as before, some of my bulbs will have smooth and linear dimming all the way down to 1%. Others will have exponential or erratic dim curves. I have one bulb that is almost identical between 25-100% almost all the dimming happens between 1-25%. Not the switches fault.

        Third - you absolutely can wire these up in 3 way, however, it is important to note that ANY dimmer on a 3 way can only have ONE dimmer. The other must always be a simple on/off. Likewise, you also CAN use another 2-way smart switch alongside this one. In order to do this, the dimmer must be the master, with the 2-way configured as the slave switch. You will NOT connect the slave switch to WiFi. Only the master needs to be connected, and this is the one you want connected so that you can control dim settings with your smart devices. Just because you dont know how to wire switches for residential doesnt make the switch defective. >_> Not the switches fault.
